Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [17]:
# Remove rows where rating is 'Not given'
food_data = food_data[food_data['rating'] != 'Not given']

# Convert ratings to numeric
food_data['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(food_data['rating'])

# Group by restaurant_name
grouped = food_data.groupby('restaurant_name')

# Filter groups having more than 50 ratings
filtered_group = grouped.filter(lambda x: x['rating'].count() > 50)

# Calculate mean ratings for each group
mean_ratings = filtered_group.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].mean()

# Get restaurants with an average rating 
# Get restaurants with an average rating greater than 4
eligible_restaurants = mean_ratings[mean_ratings > 4].index.tolist()

print("\n Restaurants that meet the advertisement offer include: {0}".format(eligible_restaurants))
print ("\n ====== Answer is complete =========================================")

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [18]:
# Write the code here

# Calculate Gross Revenue
gross_revenue = food_data['cost_of_the_order'].sum()

print ("\n ----- Method #1 of 2 -----------------------------------------\n")
def calculate_commission(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.25
    elif cost > 5:
        return cost * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

# Apply the function to the DataFrame
food_data['commission'] = food_data['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_commission)

# Calculate the total revenue
total_commission = food_data['commission'].sum()
print ("\n Net Revenue: {0}".format(gross_revenue - total_commission))
print(" Deductions: ${0}".format( total_commission))
print (" Gross Revenue: {0}".format(gross_revenue))

print ("\n ------- Method #2 of 2 ------------------------------------------ \n")
# Calculate Deductions
deductions = (food_data[food_data['cost_of_the_order'] > 20]['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.25).sum() + \
             (food_data[food_data['cost_of_the_order'] < 20]['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.15).sum()

# Calculate Net Revenue
net_revenue = gross_revenue - deductions

print ("\n Net Revenue: ${0}".format(net_revenue))

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]¶

In [19]:
# Write the code here
# Calculate total time for each order
food_data['total_time'] = food_data['food_preparation_time'] + food_data['delivery_time']

# Filter orders over 60 minutes
orders_over_60 = food_data[food_data['total_time'] > 60]

# Calculate percentage
percentage_over_60 = (len(orders_over_60) / len(food_data)) * 100

print("Percentage of orders taking more than 60 minutes:{0:2f}".format(percentage_over_60))

Recommendations and Observations:

    Day & Cost Analysis

  1. The weekday and weekend costs of food are very similar in value. I would encourage the company to look into adding discounts & specials to drive the weekday numbers up.
  2. The numbers of weekend orders are slightly more than the number of weekday orders. Thus 2 days have more orders than 5 days
  3. The average order cost of the weekend orders ($20.98) is more than the average cost of the weekday orders (17.89)
  4. This company may want to provide weekday food discounts to increase weekday sales

    5. Time: Delivery and Prep

  5. The cost of the order has a strong negative relationship to the delivery time...
    1. Preparation and delivery times are relatively consistent, with a slight correlation between the two.
    2. this could happen becuase the more costly the food order may take more cook time
    3. Maybe the more costly orders are going to wealthier neighborhoods that are farther away
    4. The food prep time is mildly related to the cost of the order

    Cruisine Analysis

  6. The most popular cruisine include American (368), Japanese (273) Italian (172) Chinese (133) and Indian (50)
  7. The least popular cruisine include Southern, French, Thai, Korean, Spanish, Vietnamese
  8. The Company should offer more of the popular cruisines (American, Japanese, Italian, Chinese) and stop offering Southern, French, Thai
  9. The cruisine the highest average costs include French ($20.00), Middle Eastern ($20) Spanish (19) and Thai (19)
  10. The cruisine the lowest average costs include Vietnemese ($12.80),Korean ($13) Mediterranean (15) and Mexican (16)
  11. The Southern French Cruisine orders have the highest order costs
  12. The Korean and Vietnamese Cruisine orders have the lowest order costs
  13. The Korean and Vietnamese order costs have outliers. There is too much variability in the order costs in these groups
  14. We can assume that the profit margin of these Korean and Vietnamese orders could be removed from the menu with no meaning impact to the gross revenue. The Company should focus on being good at a few things not everything
  15. The majority of the food orders are priced between 13 and 25 dollars
  16. The Mediterrean Cruisine has the most and highest outliers or variable costs

    17. Rating

  17. Ratings are not consistently provided, but where available, they indicate high satisfaction for Mexican and Chinese cuisines.
  18. It seems strange that some food orders have no ratings

    19. Customers:

  19. There should be a frequent customer card program to reward loyal customers
